5. Why use std::move()?

unique_ptr is

✔ Moveable
✘ Copyable

Without move

[p = ptr]

Compiler tries to copy ptr.

Compilation Error.

With move

[p = move(ptr)]

Ownership is transferred successfully.

-----------------------------------------

6. What is 'p'?

'p' is a NEW variable created inside the lambda.

Example

[p = move(ptr)]

Here

Outside lambda

ptr

Inside lambda

p

The names can even be different.

Example

[myPtr = move(ptr)]

-----------------------------------------

7. What happens to ptr?

After move

ptr == nullptr

Example

if(ptr == nullptr)
{
    cout << "Ownership transferred";
}

-----------------------------------------

8. Why not capture by reference?

Example

[&ptr]

This compiles.

But the lambda does NOT own the resource.

If ptr is destroyed before the lambda executes,
the lambda has a dangling reference.

Move capture transfers ownership safely.

-----------------------------------------

9. Where is it used?

Very common in

• std::thread
• Async programming
• Callbacks
• Event handlers
• Task queues
• Executors
• Background workers

Example

thread t(
    [p = move(ptr)]()
    {
        cout << *p;
    });

The thread becomes the owner of the unique_ptr.

-----------------------------------------

10. Difference

Capture by Value

[ptr]

Copies ptr

Works only for copyable objects.

Cannot be used with unique_ptr.

------------------------------

Move Capture

[p = move(ptr)]

Moves ownership.

Works perfectly with unique_ptr.

