11. Interview Questions

Q. What is Lambda Init Capture?

Answer:

Lambda Init Capture is a C++14 feature that allows a lambda to declare and 
initialize its own captured variables using expressions.
It is commonly used to move ownership of move-only objects like std::unique_ptr into a lambda.

-----------------------------------------

Q. Why was Lambda Init Capture introduced?

Answer:

Before C++14, lambdas could only capture existing variables by value or reference. 
Since std::unique_ptr cannot be copied, it couldn't be captured by value.
Lambda Init Capture solves this by allowing ownership to be moved into the lambda.

-----------------------------------------

Q. Why use std::move()?

Answer:

std::unique_ptr is non-copyable but movable. 
std::move converts the object into an rvalue so that ownership can be transferred to the lambda instead of copied.

-----------------------------------------

Q. What happens after std::move(ptr)?

Answer:

Ownership is transferred to the lambda's captured variable, and the original ptr becomes nullptr.

-----------------------------------------

Q. Why not capture by reference? VVVVVIVIVIVIVIVIVMP

Answer:

Capturing by reference does not transfer ownership.
If the original unique_ptr is destroyed before the lambda executes, 
the lambda will contain a dangling reference, leading to undefined behavior.

-----------------------------------------

